web_results.snippet: The American black bear, also known as the black bear, is a species of medium-sized bear endemic to North America. It is the continent's smallest and most widely distributed bear species. It is an omnivore, with a diet varying greatly depending on season and location.

related_questions.question: Are black bears aggressive or not?
related_questions.snippet: Black bears are dangerous wild animals that can act aggressively when threatened; yet there are a very low number of fatal bear attacks yearly. There is an average of one fatal black bear attack in North America every year, according to AZ Animals, which lists a total of 16 fatal attacks since 2010.
related_questions.title: Are black bears dangerous? Here's what to do if you see one in the wild.

related_questions.question: What should you do when you encounter a black bear?
related_questions.snippet: In general, when you encounter a black bear you should: • Remain calm. DON'T run from a bear. DON'T climb trees to escape a bear. Ensure the bear has an escape route.
related_questions.title: Recommendations for Human – Black Bear Encounters | Mass.gov

related_questions.question: Where does the black bear live?
related_questions.snippet: Black bears are common throughout the Pacific Northwest's forests and mountains. They are also found in forests throughout Canada, Alaska, the Rocky Mountains, the upper Midwest, parts of the southern U.S., the Appalachian Mountains, and down into Mexico.
related_questions.title: American Black Bear (U.S. National Park Service)

related_questions.question: What time of day are black bears most active?
related_questions.snippet: Bears are most active at dusk and dawn, with slightly lower activity levels during the day. They can also become nocturnal to avoid human activity. Alert and wary, they tend to avoid open areas. Individuals are solitary unless with cubs or during the breeding season.
related_questions.title: Black Bear Wildlife Note - Game Commission

buttons.subtitle: How Big Do Black Bears Get
buttons.title: Facts about Black Bears
buttons.snippet: Adult female bears, called sows, weigh about 175 pounds. Adult male bears, called boars, weigh around 400 pounds. Black bears are about 3 feet high when standing on all four feet and 5 to 7 feet tall when standing upright.
snippet_highlighted_words: about 3 feet high when standing on all four feet and 5 to 7 feet tall when standing upright

buttons.subtitle: Are American Black Bears Aggressive?
buttons.title: Human-Wildlife Conflicts: Black Bears
buttons.snippet: Black bear encounters resulting in human injury are rare in California. Bears can be unpredictable. Most black bear "attacks" are defensive actions if the animal is protecting cubs, becomes startled or scared. In some cases, a food conditioned, or habituated bear may become too bold and act aggressively towards people.
snippet_highlighted_words: In some cases, a food conditioned, or habituated bear may become too bold and act aggressively towards people

buttons.subtitle: Are American Black Bears Dangerous?
buttons.title: What to do if you encounter a black bear | Minnesota DNR
buttons.snippet: It's normal to be somewhat alarmed if you come face-to-face with a black bear. But the reality is that black bears are rarely aggressive. Actual attacks by black bears are rare. Knowing how to behave when encountering bears and how rare bear attacks actually are can keep you safe and provide peace-of-mind.

buttons.subtitle: What To Do If You See An American Black Bear?
buttons.title: What to do about black bears | The Humane Society of the United States
buttons.snippet: Stand and face the bear directly. Never run away from or approach them. Make yourself look as big as possible by spreading your arms or, better yet, a coat. Make as much noise as possible by yelling, banging pots and pans or using other noisemaking devices.

buttons.subtitle: Typical Speed Of American Black Bear
buttons.title: How Fast Can a Bear Run? + What to Do in a Bear Encounter - MeatEater
buttons.snippet: How Fast Can a Black Bear Run? Black bears are a bit slower than grizzlies but can reach top speeds of around 30 miles per hour. Their speed is going to vary based on age and athleticism.

buttons.subtitle: How Fast Can An American Black Bear Run
buttons.title: How Fast Can a Bear Run? - Yahoo
buttons.snippet: Black bears can reach speeds up to 30 mph in early spring, when they're leanest. According to the North American Bear Center, black bears can also achieve top speeds of 30 mph when they're lean. But if they're bulked up for winter and have grown thick coats, they risk overheating if they run for too long.
snippet_highlighted_words: 30 mph in early spring, when they're leanest

buttons.subtitle: American Black Bear Strength
buttons.title: What Are Some Interesting Facts About Black Bears?
buttons.snippet: Black bears are some of the strongest animals. Consider the following: Black bears can knock over 325-pound boulders with a single paw. They have a bite force of up to 800 PSI.
snippet_highlighted_words: bite force of up to 800 PSI

buttons.subtitle: What Do Black Bears Eat?
buttons.title: Black Bears - National Park Service
buttons.snippet: Black bears will eat almost anything. They are omnivores, meaning that they eat both plants and animals. Their curved claws help them climb trees to search for food, but they cannot dig for food as well as a brown bear. Black bears are very smart and can identify food not only by smell but also by appearance.

buttons.subtitle: How Many American Black Bears Are There
buttons.title: Black Bear | Defenders of Wildlife
buttons.snippet: It is estimated that there are at least 600,000 black bears in North America. In the United States, there are estimated to be over 300,000 individuals.
